Problem Statement

You are given two boxes where one contains an infinite number of blue balls and the other contains an infinite number of red balls. We can construct a chain of balls by choosing one of the boxes and inserting a ball at the end of the chain.
A chain is called "good" if after each time we insert a new ball, the number of blue balls doesn’t exceed the number of red balls by more than K (i.e., B[i] <= R[i] + K).
A chain is called "great" if it is a good chain and if we take the reversed chain, every blue ball in it is matched with a red ball in the original chain, and every red ball in the reversed chain is matched with a blue ball.

Let the probability of choosing the box with the blue balls be (B / 10^6) and the probability of choosing the red balls be (R / 10^6).
Find the probability of creating a great chain of length N modulo 10^9 + 7.

Constraints
1 <= N <= 10^9
1 <= K <= 100
1 <= B <= 10^6
1 <= R <= 10^6

